MyEigthSQLProject-CodeReview
Description: Professional review and explanation of all SQL transformations, cleaning, and BIT datatype usage applied to the heart_disease_uci dataset. Includes a step-by-step breakdown of every command.

1. Database Creation
CREATE DATABASE MyEigthSQLProject;
USE MyEigthSQLProject;
Explanation:
Created a dedicated database for this project.
USE MyEigthSQLProject ensures all subsequent commands operate within this database.
Why it matters: Separates this project from other databases for clean testing and experimentation.

2. Analyzing Table Structure
SELECT COLUMN_NAME, DATA_TYPE
FROM INFORMATION_SCHEMA.COLUMNS
WHERE TABLE_NAME = 'heart_disease_uci';
Explanation:
Lists every column and its current datatype.
Purpose: Identify columns suitable for BIT conversion (Boolean logic) or other adjustments.
Skill demonstrated: Careful dataset inspection before making changes.

3. Initial Data Analysis
SELECT * FROM heart_disease_uci;

Explanation:

Displays all rows and columns in the dataset.
Purpose: Helps identify missing values, inconsistent entries, and columns suitable for the BIT datatype.

4. Converting Gender to BIT
UPDATE heart_disease_uci
SET SEX = 1
WHERE SEX = 'Male';

UPDATE heart_disease_uci
SET SEX = 0
WHERE SEX = 'Female';

Explanation:
Converts textual gender data into BIT: 1 = Male, 0 = Female.
Why: Boolean values are more efficient for storage and easier to use in queries, filters, or analytics.

5. Working with Fasting Blood Sugar (FBS)
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET FBS = 1; -- Turns the switch on for everyone
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET FBS = 0; -- Turns the switch off for everyone

Explanation:
Shows ability to update all values in a column at once.
Useful for resetting or standardizing dataset values before applying logic per row.

UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET FBS = ~FBS;
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET FBS = 1 - FBS;

Explanation:
Demonstrates two ways to flip BIT values:
Bitwise NOT (~)
Arithmetic (1 - value)
Professional skill: Shows understanding of multiple approaches to achieve the same logic.
6. Conditional Updates with CASE
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET FBS = CASE
WHEN FBS > 1 THEN ELSE 0 END;
Explanation:
Conditional logic ensures only invalid or specific values are corrected.

Purpose: Clean dataset while avoiding unintentional overwrites.
7. Handling NULL Values with ISNULL()
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET thal = ISNULL(thal, 0);
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET chol = ISNULL(chol, 0);
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET thalch = ISNULL(thalch, 3);
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET fbs = ISNULL(fbs, 3);
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET trestbps = ISNULL(trestbps, 0);
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET ca = ISNULL(ca, 3);
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET slope = ISNULL(slope, 0);
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET exang = ISNULL(exang, 0);
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET oldpeak = ISNULL(oldpeak, 0);
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET restecg = ISNULL(restecg, 0);

Explanation:
Replaces NULL values with defaults to prevent errors in queries and calculations.
Examples:
3 indicates absence of a feature (e.g., thalch, ca)
0 indicates false/none/zero values.
Skill demonstrated: Proper data cleaning, ensuring robust dataset for analysis.

8. Setting Multiple Columns
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET FBS = 0, SEX = 1;
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET FBS = 1, SEX = 1 WHERE id = 9;
Explanation:
Updates multiple columns in one command.
Conditional update on a specific row (WHERE id = 9) demonstrates targeted data manipulation.
9. Copying Values Between Columns
UPDATE heart_disease_uci SET FBS = SEX;
Explanation:
Copies values from one column to another.
Use case: Align or sync Boolean values across columns when required.

10. Using Temporary Variables
DECLARE @MyBit BIT;
SET @MyBit = 1;
SET @MyBit = (SELECT TOP 1 sex FROM heart_disease_uci);
IF @MyBit = 1 SET @MyBit = 0;

Explanation:
@MyBit acts as a temporary storage variable.
Demonstrates procedural SQL:
Fetch a value
Store it in a variable
Apply conditional logic
Professional note: Shows ability to write reusable and procedural SQL code.

11. Handling Non-Zero Values
update heart_disease_uci SET fbs = 99;
Explanation:
Example of testing data against rules.
Later logic can convert non-zero numbers to 1 for BIT compliance.
12. Enforcing SQL Standards
SET ANSI_NULLS ON;
SET QUOTED_IDENTIFIER ON;
Explanation:

SET ANSI_NULLS ON: Ensures proper comparison of NULLs (NULL = NULL returns false unless handled).
SET QUOTED_IDENTIFIER ON: Allows use of quoted identifiers ("ColumnName" or 'TextValue') safely.
Why: Ensures queries behave predictably, especially in professional or production environments.

